04647nam a22007455i 9783112209189DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831122091897 a10.1515/97831122091892doi  a(DE-B1597)566686  a(OCoLC)1198929373  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0000002bisacsh0487u88pa494.3qDE-101222/ger1 aRentzsch, Julian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModality in the Turkic Languages :bForm and Meaning from a Historical and Comparative Perspective /cJulian Rentzsch. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (315 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudien zur Sprache, Geschichte und Kultur der Turkvölker ;v1800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tProem -- t1. Preliminaries -- t2. The Old Turkic modal system -- t3. Modality-1 -- t4. Modality-2 -- t5. Modality-3 -- t6. Survey: Formal issues -- t7. Survey: Semantic issues -- tAbbreviations -- tSources -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Turkic language family features a wealth of expressions of modality, with large inventories of items within individual languages and considerable cross-linguistic variation. Taking the hierarchy of scope between different modal classes and their link to neighboring categories as a starting point for a basic classification, the study focuses on the internal semantic subdivision of three major classes of modality together with representative formal expressions of the semantic classes from numerous modern and pre-modern Turkic languages. The evolution of particular forms and underlying abstract structure types and their dissemination throughout the Turkic languages are investigated as well as the major semantic changes that can be observed in diachrony. The paths of conventionalization identified within Turkic are compared against universal paths of grammaticalization documented in the linguistics literature. This comprehensive synchronic and diachronic survey identifies the combasic parameters of Turkic modality systems, provides an insight into the intra- and cross-linguistic diversity, and offers new perspectives for further research into this hitherto little-studied domain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package 2020z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU0 cprintz978387997447440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311220918940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783112209189423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783112209189.jpg  a978-3-11-069627-1  DG Ebook Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-069628-8  DG Ebook Package English 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-DKUb2020